Other Stressors
Although school stress and parental pressure make up a large share of the academic stress
experienced by high school students in India, a few studies observed students' stress patterns
based on various societal and demographic variables, including gender, age, socio-economic
status, and family structure. Kumar and Talwar (2014) and Deb et al. (2015) report higher stress
among girls and students in the middle of adolescence (14-16 years). These results are also
observed in the study conducted by Parikh et al. (2019), in which girls felt more restricted in
negotiating autonomy within the household, bound to prevalent sexism and expectations by
parents, and prone to risks of public sexual harassment. Stress is also observed among peers,
wherein younger adolescents are more susceptible to bullying and teasing by their school seniors
(Parikh et al., 2019). With the increasing role of social media, negative news related to students,
teachers, schools, careers, and examination policies of the education system further adds on to
academic pressure (Bhargava & Tiwari, 2019).
All these factors have resulted in a toxic environment in everyday life for school-going
students. Fear of teachers and parents and a feeling of suffocation due to an inability to express
emotional stress often results in depression and other stress reactions (Parikh et al., 2019).
Sudden and explosive anger, arguments and fights with parents, rage, and a sense of loneliness
